# Model 2 — Training Workflow

## Folder structure

```
model2/
├── app/
│   ├── embedder.py          # Semantic skill & speciality similarity
│   ├── explainer.py         # SHAP explanations
│   ├── main.py              # FastAPI endpoints
│   ├── ranker.py            # Loads trained model → predict()
│   ├── schemas.py           # Pydantic models
│   └── scorer.py            # Combines scores → final ranking
│
├── training/
│   ├── clean_dataset.py     # Step 1 — clean raw CSV
│   ├── feature_extractor.py # Step 2 — build feature vectors
│   ├── train.py             # Step 3 — train & save model
│   └── evaluate.py          # Step 4 — plots & SHAP
│
├── models/
│   ├── ranking_model.pkl    # Trained GBM model (generated)
│   ├── model_meta.json      # MAE, R², feature importances
│   └── plots/               # Evaluation plots (generated)
│
├── data/
│   ├── dataset_raw.csv      # Your original uploaded CSV (rename it)
│   └── dataset_clean.csv    # Generated by clean_dataset.py
│
└── notebooks/
    └── exploration.py       # Paste into Jupyter for EDA & report
```

## How to run

### 1. Install dependencies
```bash
pip install pandas scikit-learn sentence-transformers joblib matplotlib seaborn shap
```

### 2. Put your raw dataset in place
```bash
cp your_dataset.csv data/dataset_raw.csv
```

### 3. Clean the dataset
```bash
python training/clean_dataset.py
```

### 4. Train the model
```bash
python training/train.py
```

### 5. Evaluate & generate plots (for your PFE report)
```bash
python training/evaluate.py
```

### 6. (Optional) Run the notebook
Open `notebooks/exploration.py` in Jupyter and run cells.
Plots are saved to `models/plots/` automatically.

## What the model learns

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| `skill_score` | Semantic similarity between candidate skills and required skills |
| `speciality_score` | Similarity between candidate's speciality and job title |
| `degree_score` | Does candidate meet the degree level requirement |
| `has_university` | Whether a university name is present |
| `n_candidate_skills` | Number of skills the candidate has (normalised) |
| `n_required_skills` | Number of required skills (normalised) |
| `skill_gap_ratio` | Fraction of required skills not matched |

## Priority fields for preselection
The three highest-weight features for university/diploma/speciality are:
- `degree_score` — hard requirement check against job education requirement
- `speciality_score` — semantic match of major field to job title
- `has_university` — presence of a known institution